        "newspaperPageNumber":"43",
        "trailText":"Amir Khan's matchmaker has insisted that Golden Boy has no knowledge of a proposed bout with Floyd Mayweather and that Devon Alexander remains next on the Brit's list",
        "headline":"I have no knowledge of Mayweather bout, says Amir Khan's matchmaker",
        "body":"<p>Amir Khan's matchmaker insists he has \"no knowledge\" of a proposed mega-fight with Floyd Mayweather in May and says that the IBF welterweight champion Devon Alexander is still next in line for the Bolton fighter.</p><p>Robert Diaz, the chief matchmaker of Golden Boy Promotions – which looks after Khan's promotional interests – said he was surprised to hear suggestions that a deal to fight Mayweather was nearly done. \"I got a couple of emails on Wednesday and I said: 'What is this?' I have no knowledge of this, I haven't heard anything about this, I don't know where it is coming from. Really, I can't believe it. That subject hasn't even been brought up.\"</p><p>Diaz suggested that internet rumours mooting a Khan v Mayweather fight, coupled with the continuing delay in signing contracts for Khan to fight Alexander on 7 December, had led to the story. \"From what I am seeing, a couple of different pieces have been moved around to make it look like it was a story. I think we know who it was. To my knowledge his next fight will be on December 7 against Devon Alexander.\"</p><p>Asked why the Alexander fight is being held up, Diaz replied: \"These things are never done overnight. There's always back-and-forths, language changes. It could be something as little as fight tickets. That's why we haven't announced, but we are announcing soon.\"</p><p>Of course in boxing what is true one day can be false the next. And the closer the proposed Alexander bout gets without contracts being signed the more likely it is that the improbable could become possible and then fact. The attraction for Khan facing Mayweather, the best pound-for-pound fighter in the world, is obvious. He would earn between five to 10 times more than fighting Alexander. But he would go into such a fight having been inactive for 13 months and also moving up in weight class.</p><p>The cards would not only be stacked against him, but piled skyscraper high.</p><p>Diaz's emphatic comments reinforced those made by Khan's promotion group Team Khan earlier on Wednesday. In a statement they said: \"Team Khan would like to dispel recent reports that Amir Khan has pulled out of a potential match-up against Devon Alexander on December 7th, taking up a fight against Floyd Mayweather in May of next year instead.</p><p>\"Amir is currently in training camp in San Francisco with the aim of fighting again in December against Alexander once an agreement can be reached.\"</p><p>Meanwhile, the Olympic super-heavyweight champion Anthony Joshua has targeted a British title by the end of 2014 and a world title by 2017. Joshua, who fights the Italian Emanuele Leo in his first professional fight at the O2 Arena on Saturday, says his plan is to fight twice more in 2013 and eight times in 2014.</p><p>\"It depends on progress, step by step, but I believe it's a four-year cycle to become a world champion, just like the Olympics was between 2008 and 2012,\" he said.</p><p>When Joshua, who is keen to spar the Klitchkos and David Haye to further his development, was asked whether he could be a world champion by 2017 he nodded, adding: \"Sure it's possible.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419004910|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|62d6fc4e77c918ffd6f70a26f07512cb9d0aba6e -->",
