      "id":"sport/2013/sep/28/anthony-joshua-professional-debut",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-09-28T21:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Anthony Joshua ready for professional debut after winning Olympic gold",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/28/anthony-joshua-professional-debut",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/sep/28/anthony-joshua-professional-debut",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"11",
        "trailText":"<strong>Kevin Mitchell:</strong> Enjoying chess and keen to meet Muhammad Ali, the boxer with a real fighting gene is looking forward to stepping up",
        "headline":"Anthony Joshua ready for professional debut after winning Olympic gold",
        "body":"<p>Like a lot of big men, Anthony Joshua walks quietly, as if not to disturb the ground beneath him. His voice is soft, gentle and reassuring, his laugh and smile infectious. For a boxer of 6ft 6in and 16st-plus about to embark on a career of hurting people for a living, the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/12/anthony-joshua-wins-gold-boxing\" title=\"\">Olympic super-heavyweight champion</a> brings an unusual calmness into a room, saving the violence for the ring.</p><p>He has always been double-sided, wild in his youth but also sensitive. Out walking recently in Watford, where he grew up, Joshua was already famous but the homeless man he recognised from years before was decidedly anonymous. He walked into a chicken shop, with no money. Joshua followed him, bought them two \"No5s\", and the man said to him, \"You're that boxer. I know your story. You'll do well.\"</p><p>\"Instead of judging people,\" Joshua says, \"I listen to where they come from. This guy is an alcoholic but he's still down to earth, he knows what he is doing.\" As if the scene were scripted, Joshua saw another homeless man further down the street, and stopped to ask him: \"How did you end up here?\"</p><p>He remembers: \"His girlfriend lived in Bristol, his dad lived in Watford but was ill, so he was spending a lot of time in Watford looking after him. When his dad died, he thought he was going to inherit his place, but the council took it back and, in the meantime, he had split up with his girlfriend. So he had no family, no place to live and had been on the street for nine months.</p><p>\"What he said to me was he could go through anything in life now and nothing would break him. Being out on the streets has made his heart so tough. That's the mentality of a fighter: being so tough that nothing can break you, that street fighting mentality does resonate.\"</p><p>It would seem, then, that Joshua is well wrapped up for the wintry blasts his business almost certainly will deliver amid the sunshine. For all that he has won a silver medal at the world amateur championships and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/london-2012-olympics-blog/2012/aug/02/olympics-team-gb-boxer-anthony-joshua\" title=\"\">Olympic gold in London</a>, his resumé is thin by the sport's standards, ahead of his six-round paid debut against the unbeaten <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/26/anthony-joshua-emanuele-leo\" title=\"\">Italian Emanuele Leo at the O<sub>²</sub> Arena on Saturday</a>.</p><p>Still only 23, Joshua admits he was not even aware there was a Great Britain boxing team until Terry Edwards's squad <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/london-2012-olympics-blog/2011/mar/18/british-amateur-boxing-olympics-2012\" title=\"\">returned laden with medals from the Beijing Olympics in 2008</a>, by which time his talent had catapulted him into the lower reaches of the sport. He won the ABA title in his 18th fight, displaying maturity and no little power, and, in 16 months, rose from No46 to No1 in the world.</p><p>Having come to boxing late, he has, nevertheless, embraced its past and its intricacies. He is a tireless trainer, spending several hours a day in the gym, where he his tutored by Tony Sims, and on the running track. His was the most prized signature of the London Games, and he is happy to have <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jul/24/anthony-joshua-turns-professional\" title=\"\">joined the stable of Eddie Hearn</a>, who can provide him with regular exposure on Sky – although he has not been able to meet all his requests.</p><p>\"He sent me a text when I signed him,\" Hearn recalls. \"His demands aren't too high. He said: 'Can you sort out a meeting with Muhammad Ali?' I said: 'Yeah, hang on a minute, I'll give him a buzz.'\"</p><p>Joshua convulses – but he still wants to meet Ali. \"I've got goals to beat. Everything he achieved, to meet someone like that, just to even touch him, would be an honour. Just to meet him, to be in his presence, he could give me something that no other fighter can give me. I could take a lot of energy away from that, good vibes. I want to be just like him so to just be in his presence, the greatest of all time.\"</p><p>Joshua is a fighter with horizons beyond his discipline, which encourages the belief he will handle the mental and physical rigours of his trade well. We discuss chess, his new-found obsession; he says he will tweet his most recent mentor, Lennox Lewis, to challenge him to a game. He has given up alcohol, but not everything else. It was, \"one of my lady friends\", he reveals, laughing, who introduced him to chess.</p><p>For all that he is an amenable, articulate and engaging company, Joshua also has the fighting gene, without which the whole exercise would be futile. The last big British fighter to return from an Olympics with a gold medal, Audley Harrison, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/apr/09/audley-harrison-boxing-michael-sprott\" title=\"\">never properly tapped into that hunger for a scrap</a>, although Joshua will not be drawn into criticism of him.</p><p>\"I've got a lot more to achieve,\" he says. \"The Olympics didn't satisfy me, at all. That's what I'm trying to find in the professional world now, just to be a dominant force. I've never spoken to Audley about it. Before the Games he rang me a few times and said: 'Relax, do this and that', but I never questioned his career. Maybe, when he won and got all that admiration, that love, that attention, maybe that unsettled him.</p><p>\"There was a stage I seriously contemplated staying on [for the Rio de Janeiro Olympics] because I honestly believe that I would have won the gold again. It hadn't been done in Britain. It was the big temptation. But this is a new beginning for me. You've got to empty the cup, go in as a contender again.\"</p><p>And here he is, on the undercard of a major fight – Scott Quigg's defence of his recently awarded WBA super-bantamweight title against Yoandris Salinas. Will he be up to it, this people-savvy man with a conscience? Could the rougher end of the sport find him out?</p><p>Well, he will enter the ring to the Biggie Smalls version of the Diana Ross hit, I'm Coming Out, so he will have the ambiguity of that to deal with in a raucously male environment, but the core Joshua is a genuine fighting man.</p><p>\"Walking towards the ring, I don't want to put pressure on myself, I chill out,\" he says. \"The switch flicks as soon as I put my foot through the ropes. I just want to beat my opponent up, be too clever, counter-punching, pin him. When my feet are in range and I can land those punches, it's a great feeling. Every time I step in the ring, even when I'm sparring, I picture 20,000 people cheering. Take a walk around the ring, bell goes, on it. It's a good feeling inside the ropes. I feel comfortable in there.\"</p><p>It should be a great homecoming.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418466409|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|c69d23b7f28202bf4fbfaf9e6d6b12c8ba3309a6 -->",
